..TEXT:
|genitrice de l'onor di Cicilia e d'Aragona~:
The "honor" of Sicily (for the form ^Cicilia~, see ^Inf.~ XII,
108) is Frederick, the third son of Constance and Pedro (see n.
to vs. 115).  The "honor" of Aragon could be either Alfonso,
their eldest son, or James, their second son, who, when Alfonso
died in 1291, succeeded him in Aragon, leaving the government of
Sicily in the hands of his younger brother, Frederick, who became
king of Sicily in 1296.  In ^Purg.~ VII, 119-20 Dante expresses a
poor opinion of the worth of both Frederick and James, but (if we
assume that James rather than Alfonso is here intended) it should
be remembered that it is their grandfather who speaks of them
here as "honors."  For the view advanced by Tobler that "onor" may
mean simply ^signoria~ or, in this case, "sovereigns," see E. G.
Parodi (1901), p. 52.
..TCHR:
